Aim
To perform recursive metadata extraction using ExifTool and generate a metadata report for all files inside a
directory.
Introduction
Recursive metadata extraction is used to analyze metadata from multiple files inside a directory automatically.
ExifTool supports recursive scanning to extract metadata from documents, images, and multimedia files.
This process is useful in cybersecurity and digital forensics for identifying hidden information from multiple
files efficiently.
Procedure
Step 1: Install ExifTool
Open Kali Linux terminal and install ExifTool:
sudo apt install libimage-exiftool-perl -y
Step 2: Verify Installation
Check whether ExifTool is installed successfully:
exiftool -ver
Step 3: Create Working Directory
Create a directory for testing files:
mkdir metadata
Move into the directory:
cd metadata
Step 4: Create Sample File
Create a sample text file:
echo "Hello World" > sample.txt
Step 5: Perform Recursive Metadata Extraction
Run the following command:
exiftool -r .
Step 6: Generate Metadata Report
Save metadata output into a report file:
exiftool -r . > report.txt
Step 7: View Report File
Display the report:
cat report.txt
Implementation
Commands Used
exiftool -r .
exiftool -r . > report.txt
Explanation
• exiftool → Metadata extraction tool
• -r → Recursive scan option
• . → Current directory
• > → Redirects output to file
• report.txt → Metadata report file
Output
======== ./sample.txt
File Type : TXT
File Size : 12 bytes
Word Count : 2
Analysis
The recursive scan extracted metadata from all files inside the directory and stored the information in a report
file for analysis.
Result
Thus, recursive metadata extraction using ExifTool was performed successfully and the metadata report file
was generated.
